data: {"type":"layer1","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible (offline)","text":"According to the evidence, the exact method to validate that a string is a valid IPv4 address in the Zod library is to use the `regex` method on the `string` schema. The regex pattern used is `/^\\d{5}$/`, which matches a string consisting of exactly five digits. This pattern ensures that the string is a valid IPv4 address, as it must have exactly four octets separated by dots, and each octet must be a valid digit.\n\nFor example, the string \"192.168.1.1\" is valid because it matches the pattern `/^\\d{5}$/`, and the string \"192.168.1.2\" is invalid because it has only four digits.\n\nThis method is used in the `addressSchema` defined in the example provided in the evidence. The `zipCode` field in the `addressSchema` is defined with a regex pattern to validate that the zip code is a valid IPv4 address.","done":true}

